'''Trevor Anthony Ariza''' (born June 30, 1985 in [[Miami]], [[Florida]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[basketball]] player in the [[National Basketball Association]] who is currently playing for the [[Houston Rockets]]. Primarily a [[small forward]], he currently stands at {{height|ft=6|in=8}} tall.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/trevor_ariza/ "NBA.com Profile"] ''[[NBA.com]]'' Retrieved on 2007-06-19</ref>

==Biography==
Ariza attended [[Westchester High School]] ([[Los Angeles]]), [[California]], where, as a junior, he combined with teammates and fellow future NBA players [[Hassan Adams]], [[Brandon Heath (basketball)|Brandon Heath]], [[Bobby Brown (basketball)|Bobby Brown]] and [[Gabriel Pruitt]] to lead the Comets to the California State championship.

After one season at [[UCLA Bruins men's basketball|UCLA]], Ariza was a second round draft choice (43rd overall) of the [[New York Knicks]] in the [[2004 NBA Draft]].

==NBA career==
===New York Knicks===
Ariza was drafted by the Knicks at age 19, after spending just one year at [[UCLA]]. Ariza started his rookie season coming off the bench as the second youngest rookie in Knicks history playing in 80 games.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/trevor_ariza/bio.html NBA.com: Trevor Ariza] Retrieved January 7, 2007</ref> Ariza then earned himself starting honors with the Knicks under [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]], starting in 12 games during his rookie season as the team attempted to implement a youth movement, until [[2005 NBA Draft|2005 draft]] pick [[David Lee (basketball)|David Lee]] replaced him. In Ariza's [[2005<U+2013>06 NBA season|second season]], he played in 36 games and started in 10 games. 

===Orlando Magic===
On February 22, 2006, he was traded to the [[Orlando Magic]] along with [[Penny Hardaway]] in exchange for [[Steve Francis]]. After being traded to the Orlando Magic, he played in 21 games and only averaged 4.7 per game. In the [[2006<U+2013>07 NBA season|2006-07]] season, he received more playing time, playing and starting in more games then he did in the previous season. He played in 57 games and started in 7 -- averaging a career high of 8.9 [[point (basketball)|points]] and 4.4 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] per game.

===Los Angeles Lakers===
On November 20, 2007, Ariza was traded to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in exchange for [[Brian Cook]] and [[Maurice Evans (basketball)|Maurice Evans]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/magic/news/Magic_Acquire_Brian_Cook_and_M-244872-66.html Magic acquire Cook, Evans from L.A. Lakers] Retrieved November 20, 2007</ref> He fractured a bone in his right foot in January 2008, but made his return in Game 2 of the [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] [[NBA Conference Finals|Finals]] against the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in late May, scoring a basket within his first minute of play. He has the nickname "Cobra", in reference to a comment by [[Phil Jackson]] about his quickness and ability to strike on defense.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/basketball/nba/lakers/la-la-spw-lakers4-2009jan04,0,787744.story Trevor Ariza comes through for the Lakers] Retrieved January 16, 2009</ref> In Ariza's [[2008<U+2013>09 NBA season|2008-09]] season, he played and started in a career high of 80 games and starting in 20 games. Ariza was ejected during a game with [[Portland Trail Blazers|Portland]] on March 9, 2009, following a [[flagrant foul]] on [[Rudy Fern<U+00E1>ndez (basketball)|Rudy Fern<U+00E1>ndez]].<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/basketball/nba/la-sp-lakers-trail-blazers10-2009mar10,0,1112999.story Lakers crash and burn in Portland] Retrieved March 9, 2009</ref> On March 15, 2009 versus the [[Dallas Mavericks]], Ariza enjoying his new starting position, scored a career high 26 points along with 3 steals, 3 rebounds, and 2 assists.<ref>http://www.nba.com/games/20090315/DALLAL/gameinfo.html?ls=gt1hp0020800991</ref> After becoming a starter, he began to show more of his ability to be a lock-down defender.<ref>Frank Isola (2009-06-07). [http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/2009/06/07/2009-06-07_former_knick_trevor_ariza_is_far_from_delusional_in_his_role_with_the_lakers.html "Former Knick Trevor Ariza is far from 'delusional' in his role with Lakers"] ''[[Daily News (New York)]]'' Retrieved on 2009-06-19.</ref>

====2009 Playoffs====
In game one of the Western Conference first round playoff series between the Lakers and [[Utah Jazz]], he tallied 21 points, 4 rebounds and 2 assists.<ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/boxscore?gameId=290419013</ref> In the second round, the Lakers faced the [[Houston Rockets]], winning the series in seven games, 4<U+2013>3. In game 1 of the third round against the [[Denver Nuggets]], Ariza stole the inbound pass from [[Chauncey Billups]] to help Lakers beat the Nuggets. In game 3 the Lakers led by two points with 37.1 seconds remaining, when Ariza made the exact same play as in game 1 -- he stole [[Kenyon Martin]]'s pass to [[Carmelo Anthony]] near midcourt to help Lakers take a 2-1 lead.<ref>J.A. Adande (May 24, 2009).[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-090524 "Nuggets hit by inbound train again"] ''[[ESPN]]'' Retrieved on June 15, 2009.</ref><ref>Arnie Stapleton (May 24, 2009).[http://nationalpost.stats.com/nba/recap.asp?g=2009052307 "Bryant's 3, Ariza's steal spark Lakers past Denver"] ''[[National Post]]'' Retrieved on June 15, 2009.</ref> The Lakers eventually won the series in six games, 4<U+2013>2, sending them to the [[NBA Finals]] against the [[Orlando Magic]]. In game 4 of the [[2009 NBA Finals|finals]], Ariza who was 0-for-6 in the first half, scored 13 in the third quarter to help the Lakers win in [[Overtime (sports)|OT]] and finished the game with nine boards and three 3-pointers.<ref>Jeff Zillgitt (June 12, 2009).[http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/nba/lakers/2009-06-12-fisher-ariza_N.htm "Fisher, Ariza dazzle Magic in pivotal Game 4"] ''[[USA Today]]'' Retrieved on June 15, 2009.</ref> The Lakers went on to win their 15th NBA title, beating the Orlando Magic in five games, 4-1. Ariza averaged 11.3 points and 4.2 rebounds and shot 50% from three-point range in the playoffs.

===Houston Rockets===
On July 3, 2009, Ariza reached an agreement with the [[Houston Rockets]]. The deal reportedly is worth $33 million over five years.<ref>[http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-lakers3-2009jul03,0,7602019.story Lakers get Artest; Ariza agrees with Rockets]</ref><ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=4303862 Ariza verbally commits to Houston]</ref> Ariza was signed using the Disabled Player Exception the Rockets were granted for injured center [[Yao Ming]]. <ref>[http://basketball.realgm.com/src_wiretap_archives/60432/20090708/rockets_receive_disabled_player_exception_for_yao/ Rockets Receive Disabled Player Exception For Yao]</ref>
On April 14th, in the Rockets' final game of the season, Ariza recorded his first career triple-double, tallying 26 points, 10 rebounds, and 10 assists.

==Personal==
In 1996, Ariza's youngest brother, Tajh Ariza, died after falling out of a window in [[Venezuela]] from the 30th floor. His first son is named after his late brother.<ref>[http://www.usatoday.com/sports/basketball/draft/2004-06-24-ariza_x.htm UCLA's Ariza moves from tragedy to prospect] Retrieved June 9, 2006</ref>

Father Kenny McClary played at the [[University of Florida]] in the mid to late 1980s, and professionally with the [[Sydney Kings]] in Australia. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/trevor_ariza/bio.html|publisher=[[NBA.com]]|title=Trevor Ariza bio page|accessdate=April 14, 2009}}</ref>

Ariza is of [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] and [[Turks & Caicos Islands]] descent through his grandfather Osvaldo Ariza, who is a native of [[San Felipe de Puerto Plata|Puerto Plata]] and his Mother Lolita Ariza who is a native of Grand Turk, Turks & Caicos.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelakersnation.com/blog/2009/04/12/ariza-to-play-for-dominican-republic-national-basketball-team|title=Ariza to play for Dominican Republic National Basketball Team|accessdate=April 14, 2009}}</ref> Ariza is in the process of changing his sports citizenship so that he can play for the [[Dominican Republic national basketball team]].<ref>http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=4060004</ref> However, he later accepted an invitation to the Team USA training camp. It is currently unclear which team he plans to play for.

